# Task 1 \- C.C.

In this task, we are experimenting with the call\_shellcode.c file provided to us that was generated using the assembly shellcode. We can simply type *make* in order to generate a a32.out file and a 64.out file for 32 and 64 bit respectively. 

![][image1]

Much of the functionality that we see in the standard Ubuntu bash can be seen in this shell, we can successfully make both directories and files using this shell, and these changes are still present after we quit the shell. We can even modify the .out files and the .c code that generates this shell from within this prompt, which highlights that this shell might have permissions that could lead to problems or exploitations. However, some of the drawbacks of this shell is that we are unable to use any features of the standard bash that would open another window such as touch or nano. 

![][image2]

When we type *zsh* into the shell, we receive some information about the type of shell and some configuration options about the z shell. This shell seems to be a more advanced and extended version of the well-known bash shell. It also seems to use either the emacs or the vim style of shell navigation, which was a bit confusing to me as I am not very proficient with the commands for these types of text editors.

# Task 3 \- C.C & Connor Lariviere

After creating our badfile in the directory containing the exploit.py program, we can get the size of badfile in bytes using the *du \-h \-b* command. The value 574 will be our estimate for what to use as our start value. This value will be how far our shellcode is pushed forward in the payload.  
![][image9]

Using the gbd tool on stack-L1-dbg, we are going to print out the address of the ebp register and of the buffer once we overload our exploitable buffer. By taking the difference of these we receive the value 76, which will be the estimate for our offset.  
![][image10]

Writing the values for our start and offset into our exploit.py program.  
![][image11]  
![][image12]

The next step is to now try and determine what the return address should be by trying different values. Most values of ret will lead to either a segmentation fault or a proper return value when calling stack-L1.

![][image13]

By looking closer at the addresses inside of gbd, we can look specifically for the strcpy() function. We can see that this occurs at address 0x56556120.  
![][image14]  
Now we know how to find where the buffer starts. First, we created some basic text in badfile to look for the point in which the $esp register starts collecting information for the buffer. We do this by copying a lot of A’s (hex code 0x41) into badfile and running the program.  
By creating a breakpoint at address 0x565562d6, after strcpy() gets the information from badfile, we can then use the command *x/200xb $esp* to take a better look at the contents of memory around the esp pointer 200 bytes after that location.   
![][image15]   
Here we can see where the buffer starts. The register starts collecting information at 0xffffca62. This will be ret in our exploit.py file.  
After some testing, we discovered that the buffer holds 116 characters before a segmentation fault occurs, and that the return memory address starts at character 123\. To show this, we replaced the last two characters in our 123 character input with B (0x42) instead of A(0x41). This takes up $eip.  
![][image16]  
Tweaking the offset value and inputting the ret value 0xffffca62 in exploit.py shows us that we have successfully made esp our return address. ![][image17]  
The next step is to make that return address link to our shellcode with the start variable. It  already leads somewhere in our NOP sled, as you can see by 0xffffca62 sending to a series of 0x90’s. We also need to get our return address into $eip, since that’s our instruction pointer. This is fairly simple as $eip is only a few bytes away, and we set the offset to 122, the byte before $eip so that our return address completely overwrites the original. Running the program now gives us an empty terminal. The ‘start variable also must be set to somewhere before the offset but such that the length of the payload does not interfere with the buffer overflow. We found in this case that values between 0 and 78 work, however I started with the value 76, as that was the difference between $ebf and buffer.

![][image25]  
Upon disassembling stack-L3, we find that strcpy lies at \-0x140(%rbp), in the function with the vulnerability, bof(). The related address is

# Task 6 \- Connor Lariviere 
To start this task, I readded the dash countermeasures using $ sudo ln \-sf /bin/dash /bin/sh.  **Experiment**: Running a32.out and a64 out with and without the setuid system call. 	To start, I compiled shellcode.c using make setuid. Running both a32.out and a64.out without setuid bring you to a empty terminal (view is the same for both). It is a root-owned binary and when whoami is used, it says that you are seed. Otherwise, things seem to act like a normal terminal. ![][image29] I can run commands and programs and take other actions standard of a terminal. When these are compiled and run with the setuid added to the shellcode, The terminal looks similar. ![][image30]  It also acts like a normal shell or terminal, but this time, when whoami is used, it reveals that you are root instead of seed. This is the same for both programs. ![][image31] As an additional test, I wanted to see if I ran the seed version of one of the programs, if it would take the permissions away. I suspected not, as that is not in the scope of setuid(), but I gave it a try. After removing the setuid shellcode from a32.out and recompiling, and then running inside of the original program, I was given this result, as expected. ![][image32] After running the non-permissioned program, I am still root  **Launching Attacks:** I added the 32-bit shellcode for setuid(0) to the front of the shellcode. This meant I had to adjust how many bytes my payload was. The new shellcode added 8 bytes, and I adjusted the start value accordingly, by more than 8 bytes to be safe.

# Task 7 \- Connor Lariviere

# In this task we repeated our attack on stack-L1, this time turning the access randomization countermeasure back on using $ sudo /sbin/sysctl \-w kernel.randomize\_va\_space=2. As expected, I encountered a segmentation fault immediately, as the address I had put into exploit.py no longer leads to the same place.![][image36]  After a few more unsuccessful attempts to prove the theory, I moved on to the automated brute force approach. Using the given script in brute-force.sh, I ran the code and surprisingly I got a successful attack in only 31 seconds.![][image37] I wanted to see how long it would take to get a second successful attempt, to see if we got fortunate/unfortunate the first time or whether we hit an average time. ![][image38]

The second hit came much slower, taking about a minute (I spent two minutes with the tab open without starting it up again) and about 92,000 more attempts, almost triple what it had taken the first time. I tried again, hoping I could get a nicely aligned goldilocks scenario.   
![][image39]         
The third attempt was even slower, taking almost 5 minutes ( I again spent a few minutes before starting it up again, so it started at 6 minutes 11 seconds) and over 300,000 attempts. I can safely say that memory access randomization drastically increases the time and attempts it takes to crack even a simple buffer overflow like this, however it is still vulnerable to lucky guesses, as my first test showed. The amount of time it takes to get a hit can be extremely variable, with my longest test taking about 10 times longer than my shortest.         

# Task 8 \- C.C

In order to do an attack with StackGuard present, we have to leave it turned on with our gcc command.  
![][image40]

According to a paper written by Usenix about StackGuard, “when a buffer overflow is detected, either by the Canary or by MemGuard, the process is terminated. The process must exit, because an unknown amount of state has already been corrupted at the time the attack is detected”

[https://www.usenix.org/legacy/publications/library/proceedings/sec98/full\_papers/cowan/cowan.pdf](https://www.usenix.org/legacy/publications/library/proceedings/sec98/full\_papers/cowan/cowan.pdf)

It seems almost certain that this attack would be unsuccessful if carried out with the stack guard enabled as the program would have been terminated due to canary word that would have been placed next to the return address.  
Testing attack with StackGuard Off:   
![][image41]  
Testing Attack with StackGuard On:  
![][image42]  
As expected, StackGuard detects us attempting a buffer overflow, limiting us from exploiting it by terminating the program.
